ftware|Data Exfiltration|Compliance','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Network Communication','Prohibited protocols such as IRC, FTP, or Gopher could indicate malicious activity on insecure systems located on the network. Consider Intra-network communication, and organization accepted communications from the Internet.','Splunk Professional Services','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','None',NULL,'None','Detection of prohibited protocol (application)','UC0002',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance|Insider Threat'),(86,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise|IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','An Internet facing authentication system has allowed authenticated access from a risky source network.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Authenticated communication from a risky source network','UC0009',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(87,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise|Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','Excluding computer accounts in active directory, an account with new activity that has not been active in the previous thirty days is suspicious.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Activity on previously inactive account','UC0008',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring'),(88,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Log%20Clearing%20With%20wevtutil%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response|Windows Security','<p>This use case looks for the wevutil process clearing the Windows Audit Logs</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Log Clearing With wevtutil - Demo\nLog Clearing With wevtutil - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This use case looks for the wevutil process clearing the Windows Audit Logs','No','This use case requires Sysmon to be installed on the endpoints you wish to monitor and the Sysmon add-on installed on your forwarders and search heads.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','None at the moment','Defense Evasion','Detect Log Clearing With wevtutil','sser_detect_log_clearing_with_wevtutil','When this search fires, you will want to verify with the owner of the account responsible for clearing the Windows Logs that it was a legitimate action taken on their part.','1.1.0',NULL,'detection_suspicious_wevtutil_usage',NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(89,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Unauthorized Software|Compliance','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication|Network Communication','Authentication using insecure protocol SSH v1 detected. The legacy SSH protocol is inherently insecure indication of accepted SSHv1 sessions indicate a mis-configured system. Attempted and denied sessions indicate system probing or scanning.','Splunk Professional Services','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','None',NULL,'None','SSH v1 detected','UC0041',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(90,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Anti-Virus','Alerts when a high total number of infected hosts is discovered.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'High Number Of Infected Hosts','high_number_of_infected_hosts',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(91,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Attackers leverage an builtin Windows binary, attrib.exe, to mark specific as hidden by using specific flags so that the victim does not see the file.  The search looks for specific command line arguments to detect the use of attrib.exe to hide files.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search is looking to detect command line execution with of attrib.exe binary with the +h flag set.  The +h flag is is used to hide a file.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Defense Evasion|Persistence','Attrib.exe used to hide files/directories via commandline','detection_attrib_to_hide_files',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Windows Persistence Techniques','Advanced Threat Detection'),(92,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Data Exfiltration|Insider Threat|GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Web Proxy','Alerts on high volume web uploads by a user to non-corporate domains.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Identity',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>While not explicitly required for GDPR, this capability is often seen as a part of maintaining State of the Art Security and supports GDPR requirements.</p>','No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Web Uploads to Non-corporate Sites by Users','web_uploads_to_noncorporate_sites_by_users',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance|Insider Threat|Advanced Threat Detection'),(93,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Compliance|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','The public key utilized for authentication is recorded in the SSHD authentication log. Detection of a new key should be investigated to determine the owner of the key and validate authorization to access the resource.','Splunk Professional Services','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','None',NULL,'None','SSH Authentication using unknown key','UC0042',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Compliance'),(94,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20Local%20Admin%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail|Windows Security','<p>Local admin accounts are used by legitimate technicians, but they\'re also used by attackers. This search looks for newly created accounts that are elevated to local admins.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','New Local Admin - Demo\nNew Local Admin - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our dataset is a collection of Windows security logs for user creation and group modification. We then use the transaction command to group an account create, and an addition to the local administrators group, in a short period of time. Anything that matches, we will surface.</p>','Yes','<p>First, verify that you have Windows Security Logs coming in, and that you have implemented account change auditing (see the <a href=\"/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/data_source?datasource=Windows%20Security?technology=Windows%20Security%20Logs\">Windows Security data source documentation</a>). Once your logs are coming in, you should be able to search for <span class=\"spl\">sourcetype=\"WinEventLog:Security\" EventCode=4720 OR EventCode=4732</span> to see account creation or change events. Finally, make sure that your local admin group name is \"administrators\" so that we are looking for the right group membership changes.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Command and Control','<p>The only real source of false positives for this search would be for help desk admins who create local admin accounts. If this is common practice in your environment, you should filter out their admin account creation messages by excluding their usernames from the base search.</p><p>If your local admin group doesn\'t include the term \"administrators\" then it would potentially generate flase negatives.</p>','Defense Evasion|Persistence','New Local Admin Account','showcase_new_local_admin_account','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and capture the time of the creation, as well as the user accounts that created the account and the account name itself, the system that initiated the request and other pertinent information. Contact the owner of the system. If it is authorized behavior, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.0.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(95,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Account Compromise|Account Sharing','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','VPN','Unusual VPN Login Geolocation','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Unusual VPN Login Geolocation','unusual_vpn_login_geolocation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring|Security Monitoring'),(96,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Low','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Web Server|Web Proxy','This search looks for Web requests to faux domains similar to the one that you want to have monitored for abuse.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks at all the URLs an endpoint is connecting to and then checks the URL against a list of faux domains that could be indicative of brand abuse.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Delivery',NULL,NULL,'Monitor Web Traffic For Brand Abuse','detection_brand_abuse_web',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Brand Monitoring','Security Monitoring'),(97,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Detects when a account or credential is created and then removed a short time later. This may be an indication of malicious activities.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Short-lived Account Detected','shortlived_account_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(98,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Scanning|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Series%20of%20Discovery%20Hashes%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response','<p>It\'s uncommon to see many discovery tools launched on an endpoint, except in specific situations. This search will identify tools by file hash, and look for several in quick succession. (<a href=\"https://car.mitre.org/wiki/CAR-2016-03-001\">MITRE CAR Reference</a>)</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low (unless your company specifically does this)</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Series of Discovery Hashes - Demo\nSeries of Discovery Hashes - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our dataset is a collection of Windows process launch logs (Event ID 4688), where we have hashing turned on (look for tools like WLS, or Sysmon to help here). It then filters for a set of filenames that are known to be discovery related (from a lookup called tools.csv) and uses the transaction command to group them by time. If there\'s a single transaction with many events, it surfaces those.</p>','No','The hardest part of implementing this correctly, once you have EDR logs ingested, will be to make sure that the fields correctly set. (Why EDR? The boundary between EDR logs and Windows Security Logs for <b>most</b> Splunk customers is that Windows Process Launch Logs won\'t contain hashes, or the right variety of hashses, but EDR tools including the free Sysmon tool will.)<ul><li>In the live version, we start with index=* which is bad Splunk form (but makes it a little bit easier to get started). You should make sure that you specify the index where your EDR logs live (index=epintel if you follow our best practices, and the documentation in this app).</li><li>The next field you have to worry about is the sourcetype, which should be pretty standard.</li><li>The EventCode field is the second to last field you have to think about, which if you use our <a href=\"https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/1914/\">Splunk Add-on for Sysmon</a> on your Search Head, will also work automatically for you (again, docs are key!)</li><li>Finally, sysmon will return multiple different hashes. In order for the hashes to show up correctly in the table, make sure that you have a field named sha1 (or change the search to match what you see in the events).</ul><p>Once you have the search itself running, then you need only schedule it (click \"Schedule Alert\") and have Splunk email you, create a ticket in Enterprise Security or Service Now, or take some other action for you.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Exploitation','<p>The most likely source of false positives for this script would be normal admin activity, particularly if you have login scripts (or periodic scripts) that enumerate information about hosts, they could show up here. The easy way to filter out these situations is to look at that scripted fingerprint and filter that out. For example, using <span class=\"code\">| where</span> (which has eval-style syntax different from <span class=\"code\">| search</span>) you could filter out <span class=\"code\">| where mvcount(sha1)=4 AND sha1=\"430AA43010EEF3CD43ED445777F3D5CCF6BC4C27\" AND sha1=\"4445BC58D64BCE3322F80690AF5405876D01C0AC\" AND sha1=\"9A544E2094273741AA2D3E7EA0AF303AF2B587EA\" AND sha1=\"EA18043FEDAF888F04C07F71F2006F3F479C0B41\"</span>.</p>','Discovery','Concentration of Discovery Tools by SHA1 Hash','showcase_series_discovery_tools_hashes','<p>This alert is intended to corroborate other suspicious actions in most environments, rather than being a major flag on its own. You might send this alert to your alert manager as a low or information alert so that you can search for the asset and find it later. More advanced organizations might send this alert into the ES Risk Framework (so that you can aggregate low level risk elements) or to Splunk UBA (so that the threat models can incorporate this event into their calculations).</p>','1.0.0','Building on the two examples of surfacing concentrations of hacker or discovery tools via filename, a more accurate method for doing this is to use the SHA1 cryptographic hashes for these tools, because tools can always be renamed before executing. By correlating the process hashes being executed on endpoints with a list of \'known discovery tool executable hashes\' we can detect this suspicious activity.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring'),(99,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Hosts%20That%20Stop%20Reporting%20Sourcetypes%20-%20Live','Any Host Logs','<p>A frequent concern of SOCs is that their data feeds will disappear. This search will look on a host-by-host basis for when your security sources stop reporting home.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Live Data (Auto Accelerated)','Hosts That Stop Reporting Sourcetypes - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Here we are looking through all Splunk logs for hosts that are sending logs, but not sending Windows Security logs. We track that percentage over time, and look to see how many instances where the percentage = 0 (no Windows Logs) in the past we\'ve seen, and whether yesterday the percentage was zero.</p>','No','This search should work universally on all Splunk environments, since it uses Splunk internal fields. The only implementation detail to be aware of is specifying the index and sourcetype for the security events you care about.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Actions on Objective','<p>This alert could generate false positives depending on how noisy the security log sources in your environment are. For example, if you are looking for AV to be disabled, but you typically only get an AV message every few days, this would be difficult to reliably search for. Checking for the silence of sparse data sources is tricky to implement, and should only be attempted for advanced SPL users.</p>','Defense Evasion','Hosts Where Security Sources Go Quiet','showcase_hosts_where_sourcetypes_go_silent','<p>When this search returns values, capture the time of the event and the sourcetype that is missing. Contact the system owner. If it is known behavior, document this as well as when it is expected to be resolved. If not, further investigation is warranted to determine if the collection capability was modified, stopped, deleted or compromised.</p>','1.2.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(100,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Lateral Movement|IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Authentication','Detects excessive number of failed login attempts along with a successful attempt (this could indicate a successful brute force attack)','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Brute Force Access Behavior Detected','brute_force_access_behavior_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(101,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Data Exfiltration|GDPR|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20Risky%20Event%20Types%20Per%20User%20-%20Demo','CRM Logs|Audit Trail','<p>Salesforce.com supports a variety of different event types in their event logs. This search detects users who suddenly query event types associated with data exfiltration</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Data','Demo Data\nLive Data','New Risky Event Types Per User - Demo\nNew Risky Event Types Per User - Live',NULL,'<h4>Impact:</h4><p>First-time seen events, specifically high-risk types, can indicate unauthorized, non-compliant, and potentially malicious behavior. </p><p>Specific to GDPR, detecting first-time occurrences of high-risk behavior and proving that individuals within the organization are not abusing or misusing legitimate access to assets that store and process personal data is an industry best practice and can be considered an effective security control, as required by Article 32. This is applicable to processing personal data from the controller, and needs to also be addressed if contractors or sub-processors from third countries or international organizations access and transfer personal data (Article 15). </p>','Yes','<p>This is the generic search builder for First Seen Detection. Our dataset is an anonymized data collection from an actual customer environment.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>You should not review these alerts directly (except for high sensitivity accounts), but instead use them for context, or to aggregate risk (as mentioned under How To Respond).</p>','Collection','New High Risk Event Types for Salesforce.com User','showcase_new_sfdc_event_type','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the user demonstrating this behavior. Capture the time of the event, the user\'s role, application and number of rows exported or viewed. If possible, determine the system the user is using and its location. Contact the user and their manager to determine if it is authorized, and document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.4.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance|Insider Threat'),(102,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise|Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Network Communication','Alerts when a statistically significant increase in a particular event is observed.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Substantial Increase In Events','substantial_increase_in_events',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring'),(103,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_standard_deviation?ml_toolkit.dataset=Increase%20in%20Interactive%20Logons%20-%20Demo','Authentication|Windows Security','<p>Typically non-admin users will only interactively log into one system per day. A user who starts loggin into many can indicate account compromise and lateral movement. (<a href=\"https://car.mitre.org/wiki/CAR-2013-02-012\">MITRE CAR Reference</a>)</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','Increase in Interactive Logons - Demo\nIncrease in Interactive Logons - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect Spikes (standard deviation) search assistant. Our dataset is an anonymized collection of Windows Logon events, filtered to interactive logon types (Local: 2, RemoteInteractive: 10, Cached Local: 11). For this analysis, we are tracking the number of unique hosts the user has interactively logged into per day \'dc(host) by user _time\'. Then we calculate the average, standard deviation, and the most recent value, and filter out any users where the most recent is within the configurable number of standard deviations from average.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the Time Series Spike / Standard Deviation examples) is generally pretty simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted. If the base search you see in the box below returns results.</li><li>Save the search to run over a long period of time (recommended: at least 30 days).</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend using a summary index that first aggregates the data. We will have documentation for this process shortly, but for now you can look at Summary Indexing descriptions such as <a href=\"http://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/SplunkCloud/6.6.3/Knowledge/Usesummaryindexing\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://www.davidveuve.com/tech/how-i-do-summary-indexing-in-splunk/\">here</a>.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Installation|Actions on Objective','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately a spike in the number we\'re monitoring... it\'s nearly impossible for the math to lie. But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>How you handle these alerts depends on where you set the standard deviation. If you set a low standard deviation (2 or 3), you are likely to get a lot of events that are useful only for contextual information. If you set a high standard deviation (6 or 10), the amount of noise can be reduced enough to send an alert directly to analysts.</p>','Lateral Movement','Significant Increase in Interactive Logons','showcase_increase_interactive_logon','When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and capture the event times, the user account and systems, process and other pertinent information. Contact the owners of the systems. If it is authorized behavior, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.','1.0.0','By monitoring the number of interactively logged in users to assets, security teams can identify anomalies that may indicate the compromise of an asset or credentials. A spike in users on a particular asset could be an indicate that the asset was compromised and additional system level user accounts are being created for malicious purposes, or if they are valid credentials in AD that accounts have been compromised and the adversary is testing the accounts against a particular asset or groups of assets to test and or escalate privileges to gain deeper access to critical assets and infrastructure.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(104,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Series%20of%20Hacker%20Hashes%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response','<p>It\'s uncommon to see attacker tools used in rapid succession on an endpoint. This search will identify tools by file hash, and look for multiple executions. (<a href=\"https://car.mitre.org/wiki/CAR-2013-04-002\">MITRE CAR Reference</a>)</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Series of Hacker Hashes - Demo\nSeries of Hacker Hashes - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our dataset is a collection of Windows process launch logs (Event ID 4688), where we have hashing turned on (look for tools like WLS, or Sysmon to help here). It then filters for a set of file hashes that are known to be hacker related (from a lookup called tools.csv) and uses the transaction command to group them by time. If there\'s a single transaction with many events, it surfaces those.</p>','No','The hardest part of implementing this correctly, once you have EDR logs ingested, will be to make sure that the fields correctly set. (Why EDR? The boundary between EDR logs and Windows Security Logs for <b>most</b> Splunk customers is that Windows Process Launch Logs won\'t contain hashes, or the right variety of hashses, but EDR tools including the free Sysmon tool will.)<ul><li>In the live version, we start with index=* which is bad Splunk form (but makes it a little bit easier to get started). You should make sure that you specify the index where your EDR logs live (index=epintel if you follow our best practices, and the documentation in this app).</li><li>The next field you have to worry about is the sourcetype, which should be pretty standard.</li><li>The EventCode field is the second to last field you have to think about, which if you use our <a href=\"https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/1914/\">Splunk Add-on for Sysmon</a> on your Search Head, will also work automatically for you (again, docs are key!)</li><li>Finally, sysmon will return multiple different hashes. In order for the hashes to show up correctly in the table, make sure that you have a field named sha1 (or change the search to match what you see in the events).</ul><p>Once you have the search itself running, then you need only schedule it (click \"Schedule Alert\") and have Splunk email you, create a ticket in Enterprise Security or Service Now, or take some other action for you.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Exploitation','<p>This search should trigger very few false positives, because it\'s filtered to just very specific launches, and even more, looking for multiple process launches in a short period of time. The only scenario where you would expect to see this happen is if your organization happens to use some of those unusual tools for normal sysadmin tasks, and have them scripted. Beyond that, be suspicious!</p>','Discovery|Lateral Movement|Execution','Concentration of Attacker Tools by SHA1 Hash','showcase_series_attacker_tools_hashes','<p>This alert is very clearly tied to a known threat, so when it fires your concern is that this represents an attacker inside of one of your systems. Recommended steps are to begin incident response on the host where this alert fired from, to look for signs of other suspicious activities. The first step in that process will be to look at the parent process that launched these suspicious processes, and see what other activities that process has done. That should guide you to the underlying problem. As you get more information about this particular system (for example, how did malware end up on it, what websites has it communicated with, etc.), make sure to pivot and look across your entire organization for other indications, and to look in Open Source Intellience sites like VirusTotal to learn more about the attacker.</p>','1.0.0','Building on the two examples of surfacing concentrations of attacker or discovery tools via filename, a more accurate method for doing this is to use the SHA1 cryptographic hashes for these tools, because tools can always be renamed before executing. By correlating the process hashes being executed on endpoints with a list of \'known hacker tool executable hashes\' we can detect this suspicious activity.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring'),(105,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','High','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Authentication','This search identifies endpoints that have caused a relatively high number of account lockouts in a short period of time.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks for the Windows event code 4740 within your Windows Security Logs, which indicates that an account has been locked out. It then counts the number of times an endpoint has caused an account lockout within a four hour window and displays those hosts with a count greater than or equal to five.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Detect Excessive Account Lockouts From Endpoint','detection_excessive_lockouts_from_endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Account Monitoring and Controls','Security Monitoring'),(106,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Insider Threat|Endpoint Compromise|IAM Analytics|Privilege Escalation|Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Unusual Activity Sequence','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_6','None',NULL,'None','Unusual Activity Sequence','unusual_activity_sequence',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Insider Threat|Advanced Threat Detection|Compliance|Advanced Threat Detection|Advanced Threat Detection'),(107,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Operations|GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Ticketing System','Alerts when notable events have not been triaged','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Audit',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<h4>Impact:</h4><p>Detecting and proving that priority alerts indicating potential risk to security posture are not being processed in a timely manner is an industry best practice.</p><p>Specific to GDPR, this method is considered an effective security control, as required by Article 32. Demonstrating that noteworthy activity is being triaged and appropriately escalated will help to prove compliance for data privacy audits from authorities (Article 58) or counteract any compensation claims (Article 82). </p>','No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_5',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Untriaged Notable Events','untriaged_notable_events',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(108,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=First%20Connection%20to%20Domain%20Controller%20-%20Demo','Windows Security','<p>A common indicator for lateral movement is when a user starts logging into new domain controllers.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','First Connection to Domain Controller - Demo\nFirst Connection to Domain Controller - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our dataset is a anonymized collection of Windows domain controller logon events (Event ID 4776). For this analysis, we are effectively grouping by username and domain controller name, which will give us a row for each username+domaincontrollername combination. We check if the first time that has occurred was in the last day.</p>','Yes','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Installation','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>You should not review these alerts directly (except for high sensitivity accounts), but instead use them for context, or to aggregate risk (as mentioned under How To Respond).</p>','Lateral Movement','Authentication Against a New Domain Controller','showcase_first_seen_domain_controller','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the user account accessing the specific domain controller. Contact the user and system owner about this action. If it is authorized, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted to determine that lateral movement is not occurring.</p>','1.0.0','Once an attacker gains access to a network either through a compromised asset or credentials, most will attempt to then move laterally within the network targeting critical infrastructure. As domain controllers provide the physical storage for the Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) database, in addition to providing the services and data that allow enterprises to effectively manage endpoints (servers and workstations), users, and applications. If privileged access to a domain controller is obtained by a malicious user, that adversary can modify, corrupt, or destroy the AD DS database and, along with all of the systems and accounts that are managed by Active Directory. By monitoring both successful and unsuccessful authentication attempts organizations can identify anomalies such as time of day, frequency and other suspicious patters that may indicate compromised assets or credentials.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(109,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Account Compromise|Scanning','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Basic%20Brute%20Force%20-%20Demo','Windows Security','Uses a simple threshold for Windows Security Logs to alert if there are a large number of failed logins, and at least one successful login from the same source.','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','Basic Brute Force - Demo\nBasic Brute Force - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized Windows Authentication logs, during which someone attempts a brute force against a series of usernames. Our live search looks for Windows Authentication activity across any index in the standard sourcetype.','Yes','If you have followed the data onboarding guides in this app, this search will work immediately for you. You should generally specify the index where you are storing Windows Security logs (e.g., index=oswinsec), and if you use a mechanism other than the Splunk Universal Forwarder to onboard that data, you should verify the sourcetype and fields that are used. The rest is simple!',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,'The only known scenario where this search could generate false positives is if you have a single source (for example, a web app) that centralizes the authentication for many people. In that scenario, you might need to adjust thresholds for that source, or exclude it and build a separate similar search just using the logs from that host.','Credential Access','Basic Brute Force Detection','basic_brute_force','When this search fires, the immediate concern is that the brute force search was successful. See if it is coming from a host that typically logs in with that account to make sure it is not just coincidental, and then reset the password for any compromised accounts and look for any other places where that username was used.','2.0.0','Discovering real credentials is a key component for any attacker. While there are many approaches for doing that, a time honored way is to find weak passwords by just trying hundreds of common passwords. Particularly as most environments use Active Directory as their central storage respository for credentials, looking for brute force activity in Windows Security logs should be a component of any security strategy.','excessive_failed_logins\nbrute_force_access_behavior_detected_over_one_day\nUC0109\nUC0108\nmultiple_logins\nmultiple_login_errors',NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(110,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','IAM Analytics|Account Sharing|Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Authentication','Alerts on concurrent access attempts to an app from different hosts. These are good indicators of shared passwords and potential misuse.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Concurrent Login Attempts Detected','concurrent_login_attempts_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(111,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Insider Threat|Account Compromise|IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Authentication|Windows Security','Period with Unusual AD Activity Sequences','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_6','None',NULL,'None','Period with Unusual AD Activity Sequences','period_with_unusual_ad_activity_sequences',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat|Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(112,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Command and Control','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','DNS','Malicious actors often abuse legitimate Dynamic DNS services to host malicious payloads or interactive command and control nodes. Attackers will automate domain resolution changes by routing dynamic domains to countless IP addresses to circumvent firewall blocks, blacklists as well as frustrate a network defenders analytic and investigative processes. This search will look for DNS queries made from within your infrastructure to suspicious dynamic domains.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','The search is querying an accelerated Network_Resolution data model to count and list the values of resolved domains for each DNS query and checks that against the list of Dynamic DNS providers (lookup - dynamic_dns_providers) by each host (DNS.src)','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control|Actions on Objective',NULL,'Exfiltration|Defense Evasion','Detect hosts connecting to dynamic domain providers','detection_dyn_dns_queries',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Suspicious DNS Traffic','Advanced Threat Detection'),(113,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Command and Control|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','DNS','Alerts when a host receives many DNS failures in a short span','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Excessive DNS Failures','excessive_dns_failures',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(114,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise|Unauthorized Software','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Alerts when an anomalous number hosts are detected with a new process.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Anomalous New Process','anomalous_new_process',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(115,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Anti-Virus','Alerts when a host has an infection that has been re-infected remove multiple times over multiple days.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,'Execution','Host With A Recurring Malware Infection','host_with_a_recurring_malware_infection',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(116,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Account Compromise|Account Sharing','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Land Speed Violation','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Land Speed Violation','land_speed_violation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring|Security Monitoring'),(117,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Short%20Lived%20Accounts%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail|Windows Security','<p>A technique used by attackers is to create an account, take some actions, and then delete it right away. This search will find those accounts on the local system.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data\nAccelerated Data','Short Lived Accounts - Demo\nShort Lived Accounts - Live\nShort Lived Accounts - Accelerated',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our dataset is a collection of Windows security logs for user creation and user deletion. We filter for that, and then use the transaction command to group a create and delete in a short period of time. Anything that matches, we will surface. </p>','No','This search relies on the standard Windows Security events coming from a Windows Forwarder on a workstation or member server (so: not domain controllers). Implementation is as easy as just ingesting that data, specifying the correct index, and then running the search. If you are using a log source other than the Splunk TA for Windows (e.g., snare, WMI, etc.), you might need to adjust field names to match those in the search itself.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Command and Control','<p>The biggest potential false positive from this detection is that technically it will fire for any account creation, not just admin accounts. It\'s difficult to put sufficient logic into a single search to detect admin accounts while also detecting short lived accounts (though it may be possible to combine with the new admin acccount detection in this app), and wasn\'t a big priority given how rare short lived accounts are in general.</p><p>Beyond that, there are no known sources of false positives for this search.</p>','Defense Evasion|Persistence','Short Lived Admin Accounts','showcase_short_lived_accounts','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and capture the time of the creation and deletion events, as well as the user accounts that created the account and the account name itself, the system that initiated the request and other pertinent information. Contact the owner of the system. If it is authorized behavior, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.0.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(118,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Authentication','Discovers accounts that are no longer used. Unused accounts should be disabled and are oftentimes used by attackers to gain unauthorized access.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Completely Inactive Account','completely_inactive_account',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance|Security Monitoring'),(119,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Insider Threat|Account Compromise|IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Authentication|Windows Security','Unusual Machine Access','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_6','None',NULL,'None','Unusual Machine Access','unusual_machine_access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat|Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(120,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise|Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Authentication|Anti-Virus','Detects users with a high or critical priority logging into a malware infected machine','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'High or Critical Priority Individual Logging into Infected Machine','high_or_critical_priority_individual_logging_into_infected_machine',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(121,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Operations|Compliance|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Outdated%20Malware%20Definitions%20-%20Demo','Anti-Virus','Looks for Symantec AV systems where we see Symantec AV events, but don\'t see a malware definition update in the last few days.','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Outdated Malware Definitions - Demo\nOutdated Malware Definitions - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Simple Search search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized Symantec Endpoint Protection logs (onboarded in accordance with our Data Onboarding Guides), during which someone does something bad. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the standardized sourcetypes for Symantec Endpoint Protection or the Common Information Model.','No','This particular search usually finds most of its success with just Symantec AV. Many Anti-Virus products are found to provide insufficient logging to be able to see when the definitions are updated (often, just when there is malware found). If you are using Symantec AV and followed the data onboarding guide, this should work automatically. If you did not follow the data onboarding guide, make sure that your sourcetypes and indexes match. Always hardcode your sourcetypes and indexes rather than doing index=* in searches.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,'No known false positives at this time.',NULL,'Outdated Malware Definitions','Outdated_Malware_Definitions','When this fires, look on the host to see why the Anti-Virus isn\'t updating. If you don\'t see an obvious reason (e.g., specific and logical error), then it may be worth investigating that host to see if there are any other suspicious events that have occurred to rule out an infection.','2.0.0','This indicates that a host is not updating its anti-virus definitions, which can be an operational concern (e.g., anti-virus isn\'t working), or it could be an indication that updates have been shut off by malware itself. Regardless, it is something to fix.',NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(122,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Low','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Email','This search looks for emails claiming to be sent from a domain similar to one that you want to have monitored for abuse.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks at the sender address in email headers, and identifies those with a sender address using a domain name that matches the list of permutations generated for the domain you want to monitor.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Delivery',NULL,NULL,'Monitor Email For Brand Abuse','detection_brand_abuse_email',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Brand Monitoring','Security Monitoring'),(123,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Data Exfiltration|GDPR|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20Applications%20Contacting%20SFDC%20-%20Demo','CRM Logs|Audit Trail','<p>Salesforce.com contains the most critical information for many companies. This search looks for users who connect to SFDC\'s reporting API with new clients. </p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Data','Demo Data\nLive Data','New Applications Contacting SFDC - Demo\nNew Applications Contacting SFDC - Live',NULL,'<h4>Problem:</h4><p>Many organizations maintain business-critical information within SaaS applications such as Salesforce.com. Salesforce is an example of a CRM business application which is used to store and process personal data relating to customers, partners, prospects and often employees. As part of a Salesforce.com deployment, other applications interact with this sensitive data, via push or pull APIs that automate data exchange - for example integrations into finance and human resources applications such as Workday, or marketing automation tools such as Eloqua and Marketo. Attackers can attempt to use the Salesforce.com API as a vector to gain access to sensitive data. Because Salesforce.com is a cloud application with a publicly accessible domain, this vector only requires valid credentials, and can be exploited for access to sensitive data by adversaries, even if they lack access to internal resources.</p><h4>Impact:</h4><p>Under the GDPR Article 30, organizations are required to maintain a record of processing activities including contact details of the controller, the purposes of processing, description of the categories of data subjects and personal data processed -- as well as the categories of recipients to whom the personal data has been or will be disclosed including recipients in any other countries. Interactions from new applications -- whether for legitimate purposes or as a result of malicious activity -- can create a non-compliance condition if they are not documented properly. This situation may not impact organizations who employ fewer than 250 persons and therefore may not have critical categories of personal data for processing.</p><h4>Resolution Path:</h4><p>Monitoring Salesforce.com API activity can help identify connections from new applications or clients that might not be whitelisted or documented. The timely and accurate reporting of a non-compliance state can prompt the Data Privacy Officer to proactively follow up and update documentation, and report to the authorities in a timely manner if appropriate.</p>','Yes','<p>This is the generic search builder for First Seen Detection. Our dataset is an anonymized data collection from an actual customer environment.</p>','Yes','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>You should not review these alerts directly (except for high sensitivity accounts), but instead use them for context, or to aggregate risk (as mentioned under How To Respond).</p>','Collection','New Application Accessing Salesforce.com API','showcase_new_sfdc_clients','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the user demonstrating this behavior. Capture the time of the event, the user\'s role, and application. If possible, determine the system the user is using and its location. Contact the user and their manager to determine if it is authorized, and document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.4.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance|Insider Threat'),(124,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Ransomware%20Extensions%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response|Windows Security','<p>This example queries your endpoint data to find encrypted files that ransomware will create. You can often even use these extensions to identify the ransomware affecting a given endpoint.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Ransomware Extensions - Demo\nRansomware Extensions - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This use case is designed to query your endpoint data to look for encrypted files that ransomware creates. Most ransomware families use a consistent extension for the encrypted files they generate, so you can use those extensions to identify the ransomware affecting a given endpoint.','No','This search requires Sysmon to be installed on your endpoints with the Sysmon add-on installed on your forwarders and search heads. Common ransomware extensions and the associated ransomware families are located in the ransomware_extensions.csv lookup file. You can update this list to reflect the latest intelligence without the need to modify the search.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','None at the moment',NULL,'Ransomware Extensions','sser_ransomware_extensions','When this search fires, you will want to start your incident response process for dealing with a ransomware infection.  You should check for recent backups for the systems effected by the infection.','1.0.0',NULL,'detection_common_ransomware_extensions',NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(125,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20Parent%20Process%20for%20cmd.exe%20or%20regedit.exe%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response|Windows Security','<p>cmd.exe and regedit.exe tend to be used in the same ways. New parent processes can be suspicious. (<a href=\"https://car.mitre.org/wiki/CAR-2013-02-003\">MITRE CAR Reference</a>)</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','New Parent Process for cmd.exe or regedit.exe - Demo\nNew Parent Process for cmd.exe or regedit.exe - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our dataset is a anonymized collection of Windows domain controller logon events (Event ID 4776). For this analysis, we are effectively grouping by username and domain controller name, which will give us a row for each username+domaincontrollername combination. We check if the first time that has occurred was in the last day.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted. <b>For this search</b> you may wish to alter the process names that are tracked.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Exploitation','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>This detection should have relatively few false positives given the rarity of new parent processes for these standard Windows processes. Most noise that will come from new systems management scripts, or from new software installers. These can be whitelisted in the search.</p>','Discovery|Lateral Movement|Execution','New Parent Process for cmd.exe or regedit.exe','showcase_new_parent_process_for_cmd','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the parent process that initiated cmd.exe or regedit.exe. Determine the user account this is running under and the system it is running on. Contact the user and system owner of this action. If it is authorized, document that this is and by whom. If not, the user credentials have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted to ensure that processes are not spawning these commands.</p>','1.0.0','As described above, we want to carefully monitor certain executables on our Windows endpoints and understand what is calling them. For example, if we see a program like Word or Excel launching cmd.exe, it is probably up to no good especially if we??ve never seen it do that before. Programs that behave in this way legitimately should be whitelisted - others should be immediately investigated.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(126,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Detects changes to policies of the network protection devices (such as firewall policy changes).','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Network Change Detected','network_change_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(127,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Web Proxy','Suspicious HTTP redirects','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_6','None',NULL,'None','Suspicious HTTP redirects','suspicious_http_redirects',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(128,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Endpoint Compromise|Unauthorized Software','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Web Proxy','Unusual Web Browser','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Unusual Web Browser','unusual_web_browser',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring'),(129,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Data Exfiltration|Command and Control|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','DNS','Endpoint utilizing DNS as a method of transmission for data exfiltration, command and control, or evasion of security controls. Detected by large total size of DNS traffic OR large number of unique queries.','Splunk Professional Services','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Detection of DNS Tunnel','UC0049',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat'),(130,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for powershell processes started with parameters to modify the execution policy of the run, run in a hidden window, and connect to the Internet. This combination of command line options is suspicious because it\'s overriding the default powershell execution policy, attempts to hide its activity from the user, and connects to the Internet.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks for powershell processes running with specific command line arguments that indicate that the process will download a file from the internet without display anything to the user. The search for \"*-Exec*\" is to check and see if the default execution policy for powershell is being overridden on the command line. The search for \"*-WindowStyle*\" and \"*hidden*\" are to see if the window that would normally be displayed will be hidden from the user instead. Finally, the search for \"*New-Object*\" and \"*System.Net.WebClient*\" are there to check to see if a powershell object that can be used to download files will be created. This search will return the host, the user the process ran under, the process and it\'s command line arguments, the number of times it\'s seen this process, and the first and last times it saw this process.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control|Actions on Objective',NULL,'Execution','Malicious PowerShell Process - Connect To Internet With Hidden Window','detection_malicious_powershell_process_connect_to_internet_with_hidden_window',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Malicious PowerShell','Advanced Threat Detection'),(131,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Insider Threat','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Authentication','Alerts when an event is discovered from a user associated with identity that is now expired (that is, the end date of the identity has been passed).','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Identity',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Activity from Expired User Identity','activity_from_expired_user_identity',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Insider Threat|Security Monitoring'),(132,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','High','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Account Compromise|IAM Analytics|Account Sharing|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=AWS%20Cloud%20Provisioning%20Activity%20from%20Unusual%20IP%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail','Looks for AWS Provisioning activities that occur from new IPs (for organizations with strict IP controls).','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','AWS Cloud Provisioning Activity from Unusual IP - Demo\nAWS Cloud Provisioning Activity from Unusual IP - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized AWS CloudTrail logs, during which someone does something bad. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the very standardized index and sourcetype for AWS CloudTrail, as detailed in How to Implement.','No','Assuming you use the ubiqutious AWS Add-on for Splunk to pull these logs in, this search should work automatically for you without issue. While implementing, make sure you follow the best pratice of specifying the index for your data.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,'<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p><p>For most organizations, this search is not going to be useful apart from contextual data (i.e., when we are analyzing another alert related to account compromise, we can also see that this user logged in from an unsual IP). The reason is that most organizations don\'t apply strict controls to what IPs are allowed to reach out to their AWS orchestration environments. However, if your organization does have strict controls, and all of a sudden a new IP shows up, that could be very noteworthy. </p>',NULL,'AWS Cloud Provisioning Activity from Unusual IP','AWS_Cloud_Provisioning_Activity_from_Unusual_IP','For organizations that have strict allowed IPs for cloud orchestration, you may opt to use Splunk\'s Adaptive Response Actions to automatically disable an account that is doing provisioning from a new IP. More commonly, the concern is account compromise so it is prudent to immediately call the user and find out if they intended to take those actions.','2.0.0','The risk that this detection intends to reduce is the compromise of an AWS environment, where all of a sudden provisioning occurs from IP Addresses that have not been seen before (only applicable for organizations that have strict policies around IP Addresses for AWS Access). Assuming that the user is not traveling, and that new orchestration tools are not being used, this would suggest that credentials have been created or compromised, and are in control of an adversary. This could result in potential data leakage, data deletion, or cost run-up.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(133,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Scanning','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','IDS or IPS','Detects a potential vulnerability scanner by detecting devices that have triggered events against a large number of unique targets. Vulnerability scanners generally trigger events against a high number of unique hosts when they are scanning a network for vulnerable hosts.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Vulnerability Scanner Detected (by targets)','vulnerability_scanner_detected_by_targets',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(134,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise|Compliance|Network Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','Even using SSH encryption, allowing password authentication to Linux/Unix systems over the network increases the attack surface and the possible impact of a compromised account. Investigate and resolve all instances of network authentication utilizing password.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Network authentication using password auth','UC0044',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(135,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Failure to synchronize time will impact the usefulness of security log data from the endpoint, and potentially prevent valid authentication.','Splunk Professional Services','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','None',NULL,'None','Endpoint failure to sync time','UC0046',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(136,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Low','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for shim database files being written to default directories. The sdbinst.exe application is used to install shim database files (.sdb). According to Microsoft, a shim is a small library which transparently intercepts an API, changes the parameters passed, handles the operation itself, or redirects the operation elsewhere.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks files being created in Windows\\AppPatch\\Custom and Windows\\AppPatch\\Custom64, the location where shim databases are installed to. It will return all the files created and the time of the first and last file creation of those files for each endpoint.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Persistence','Shim Database File Creation','detection_shim_database_file_creation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Windows Persistence Techniques','Advanced Threat Detection'),(137,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Web Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Web Proxy','Alerts when a host has an abnormally high number of HTTP requests by http method.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Abnormally High Number of HTTP Method Events By Src','abnormally_high_number_of_http_method_events_by_src',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Application Security|Advanced Threat Detection'),(138,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Command and Control|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','DNS','Alerts when a host starts sending excessive DNS queries','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Excessive DNS Queries','excessive_dns_queries',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(139,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Lateral Movement|Endpoint Compromise|GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Network Communication','Detects the use of ports that are prohibited. Useful for detecting the installation of new software or a successful compromise of a host (such as the presence of a backdoor or a system communicating with a botnet).','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>While not explicitly required for GDPR, this capability is often seen as a part of maintaining State of the Art Security and supports GDPR requirements.</p>','No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Prohibited Port Activity Detected','prohibited_port_activity_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Compliance'),(140,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/gdpr_investigation?load=1','Any Host Logs|Network Communication|Web Proxy|Windows Security','Meeting your compliance requirements necessitates being able to investigate breaches. Splunk ES provides you a single place to fully understand attacker activities.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Data',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Investigate GDPR Breaches Using ES','gdpr_investigation',NULL,'2.1.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance'),(141,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','Following a successful authentication, an attacker will attempt to determine what resources may be accessed without causing host intrusion or DLP technologies to detect activity. Commonly the attacker will enumerate and browse to shares, access email, access web applications, or connect to databases yet perform minimal or no activity.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','None',NULL,'None','Compromised account access testing','UC0035',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(142,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','Following a successful authentication, an attacker will attempt to determine what resources may be accessed without causing host intrusion or DLP technologies to detect activity. Commonly the attacker will enumerate and browse to shares, access email, access web applications, or connect to databases yet not perform any or minimal activity. Typically Critical and Sensitive systems (during routine use) would not log access denied events.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','None',NULL,'None','Compromised account access testing (Critical/Sensitive Resource)','UC0036',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(143,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Network Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','IDS or IPS','IDS devices reporting an attack using a signature not previously encountered are more likely be successful as new signatures are prompted by newly know attacks in the wild.','Splunk Professional Services','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','None',NULL,'None','Network Intrusion - New Signatures','UC0037',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(144,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','GDPR|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Endpoint%20Uncleaned%20Malware%20-%20Demo','Anti-Virus','Detect a system with a malware detection that was not properly cleaned, as they carry a high risk of damage or disclosure of data.','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','Endpoint Uncleaned Malware - Demo\nEndpoint Uncleaned Malware - Live',NULL,'<h4>Problem</h4><p>Despite initial detection from traditional anti-malware tools, malware often persists undetected on endpoints. This can occur when malware uses evasive techniques to spread to other endpoints without triggering an alert, or if an infection or re-infection occurs due to incomplete remediation or a response that does not address the root of the infection.</p><h4>Impact</h4><p>Uncleaned malware puts digital systems at risk. For any environments/systems that are involved in processing personal data, this situation can be critical, and especially so in a GDPR context. <b>Article 32</b> of the GDPR requires that organizations regularly test, assess and evaluate effectiveness of implemented technical and organizational security controls. In the event that a Supervisory Authority executes powers to place an organization within the scope of a privacy audit, the organization must demonstrate compliance (<b>Article 58</b>). If the organization faces a personal data breach and individuals are impacted, those individuals have the right to demand compensation for material and non-material damage caused by the breach. The organization must prove that they have understood and addressed the risk appropriately and deployed proper countermeasures (<b>Article 82</b>). </p><h4>Resolution Path</h4><p>Removing malware infections that antivirus and other legacy endpoint protection software cannot remove (whether due to file permissions or other configurations that prevents easy quarantine or cleaning) can be considered in many cases appropriate, and helps to demonstrate compliance</p>.','Yes','This example leverages the Simple Search search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized Symantec Endpoint Protection logs (onboarded in accordance with our Data Onboarding Guides), during which a virus is not cleaned. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the standardized sourcetypes for Symantec Endpoint Protection or the Common Information Model.','Yes','With Anti-Malware logs onboard, these searches should work easily, particularly if you use a Splunk Add-on that maps the logs to the Common Information Model (search on Splunkbase!).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,'No known false positives at this time.',NULL,'Endpoint Uncleaned Malware Detection','UC0030','When this occurs, you should begin a standard incident response process on this host.','2.0.0','For all the environments, uncleaned malware means that there is still malware located in your environment. For environments that are handling GDPR, article 32 requires that you regulary test, assess and evaluate the effectiveness of your implemented technical and organizational security controls. If the Authority executes their powers and your Organization is in the scope of a Privacy Audit you need to demonstrate compliance (Article 58). Also in case you face a breach and individuals are impacted they have the right to compensation of the damage - if an organization can prove that they have done everything approriate to the risk and deployed proper countermeasures, they shouldn\'t be liable (Article 82). Clearing out viruses can be considered in most cases as appropriate and your organization should be able to prove compliance.',NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(145,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Accounts designated for use by services and batch process should start a limited set of child processes. Creation of new child processes other than the process name defined in the service or batch definition may indicate compromise.','Splunk Professional Services','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Service Account Starting Unexpected Processes','UC0031',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(146,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Data Exfiltration','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Network Communication','This search looks for network traffic identified as The Onion Router (TOR), a benign anonymity network which can be abused for a variety of nefarious puproses.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','The search leverages the Enterprise Security Network_Traffic data model to look for network traffic that has been identified as TOR and marked as \'allowed\'.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','Command and Control',NULL,'Command and Control|Exfiltration','TOR Traffic','detection_tor_traffic',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Ransomware','Insider Threat|Security Monitoring'),(147,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for powershell processes that have encoded the script within the command line. Malware has been seen using this parameter, as it obfuscates the code and makes it relatively easy to pass a script on the command line.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks for powershell processes that are passing encoded commands on the command line. The flags \"-EncodedCommand\" and \"-enc\" are two different possible flags that can be used to pass base64 encoded commands to powershell.  This search will return the host, the user the process ran under, the process and it\'s command line arguments, the number of times it\'s seen this process, and the first and last times it saw this process.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control|Actions on Objective',NULL,'Execution','Malicious PowerShell Process - Encoded Command','detection_malicious_powershell_process_encoded_command',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Malicious PowerShell','Advanced Threat Detection'),(148,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Other','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','IDS or IPS','External Alarms','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','External Alarms','external_alarms',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Other'),(149,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Low','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Email','This search looks for emails that have attachments with suspicious file extensions.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks at any email messages with attachments and checks the file names of those attachments against an included lookup file to see if it has a suspicious file extension.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Delivery',NULL,'Execution|Defense Evasion','Suspicious Email Attachment Extensions','detection_suspicious_email_attachments',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Suspicious Emails','Security Monitoring'),(150,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for dlls under %AppData% being loaded by rundll32.exe that are calling the exported function at ordinal 2. Calling exported functions by ordinal is not as common as calling by exported name. There was a bug fixed in IDAPro on 2016-08-08 that would not display functions without names.  Calling functions by ordinal would overcome the lack of name and make it harder for analyst to reverse engineer.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks for rundll32.exe being run, loading a DLL out of a directory or subdirectory of AppData, and specifying the function at ordinal 2 be run.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Installation',NULL,'Execution','RunDLL Loading DLL By Ordinal','detection_rundll_loading_dll_by_ordinal',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Unusual Processes','Advanced Threat Detection'),(151,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Data Exfiltration|GDPR|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20SFDC%20Tables%20Queried%20by%20User%20-%20Demo','CRM Logs|Audit Trail','<p>Salesforce.com supports a simplified query language called SOQL. This search detects users who begin querying new sensitive tables.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Data','Demo Data\nLive Data','New SFDC Tables Queried by User - Demo\nNew SFDC Tables Queried by User - Live',NULL,'<h4>Impact:</h4><p>Detecting first-time query attempts to sensitive tables by a user who has previously not accessed the tables in question, can help prove that individuals within the organization are not abusing or misusing legitimate access to assets.</p><p>This can relate to GDPR in that in-scope assets will store and process personal data. This method is an industry best practice and can be considered an effective security control, as required by Article 32. This is applicable to processing personal data from the controller, and needs to also be addressed if contractors or sub-processors from third countries or international organizations access and transfer personal data (Article 15). </p>','Yes','<p>This is the generic search builder for First Seen Detection. Our dataset is an anonymized data collection from an actual customer environment.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>You should not review these alerts directly (except for high sensitivity accounts), but instead use them for context, or to aggregate risk (as mentioned under How To Respond).</p>','Discovery|Collection','New Tables Queried by Salesforce.com User','showcase_new_sfdc_tables','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the user demonstrating this behavior. Capture the time of the event, the user\'s role, and tables queried. If possible, determine the system the user is using and its location. Contact the user and their manager to determine if it is authorized, and document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.4.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance|Insider Threat'),(152,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise|GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Anti-Virus','Alerts when a host with an old infection is discovered (likely a re-infection).','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<h4>Impact:</h4><p>Similar to Detection of Uncleaned Malware on Endpoint ?? uncleaned malware puts digital systems at risk. For any environments/systems that are involved in processing personal data, this situation can be critical, and especially so in a GDPR context. Article 32 of the GDPR requires that organizations regularly test, assess and evaluate effectiveness of implemented technical and organizational security controls. In the event that a Supervisory Authority executes powers to place an organization within the scope of a privacy audit, the organization must demonstrate compliance (Article 58). If the organization faces a personal data breach and individuals are impacted, those individuals have the right to demand compensation for material and non-material damage caused by the breach. The organization must prove that they have understood and addressed the risk appropriately and deployed proper countermeasures (Article 82). </p><h4>Resolution Path:</h4><p>Removing malware infections that antivirus and other legacy endpoint protection software cannot remove (whether due to file permissions or other configurations that prevents easy quarantine or cleaning) can be considered in many cases appropriate, and helps to demonstrate compliance.</p>','No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,'In ES, the Malware Operations Center provides lots of powerful visibility into the malware status of your organization.','Malware Operations Center','/static/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/images/example_images/es_host_with_reinfection_1.png','Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Host With Old Infection Or Potential Re-Infection','host_with_old_infection_or_potential_reinfection',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(153,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Web Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Network Communication|Host-based IDS','Using web application access logs for assets deemed high/critical or with the governance attributed ensure the source IP address is one of the approved NLB or WAF devices. If WAF devices are placed in front of NLB devices ensure the first &quot;x-forwardedfor&quot; entry is the address of the WAF.','Splunk Professional Services','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Exception to Approved Flow for Web Applications','UC0092',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Application Security'),(154,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Other','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','DLP','Multiple DLP Alarms','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Multiple DLP Alarms','multiple_dlp_alarms',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Other'),(155,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','High','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Account Compromise|IAM Analytics|Insider Threat|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=AWS%20New%20API%20Call%20Per%20User%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail','Looks for users that are using AWS APIs that they\'ve never used before.','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','AWS New API Call Per User - Demo\nAWS New API Call Per User - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized AWS CloudTrail logs, during which someone does something bad. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the very standardized index and sourcetype for AWS CloudTrail, as detailed in How to Implement.','Yes','Assuming you use the ubiqutious AWS Add-on for Splunk to pull these logs in, this search should work automatically for you without issue. While implementing, make sure you follow the best pratice of specifying the index for your data.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,'<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p><p>Specifically for AWS, they have many APIs (and create new ones regularly!), so it\'s generally best to tune over time for which APIs you actually want to be emailed about, leave the rest for context, or to aggregate risk.</p>',NULL,'AWS New API Call Per User','AWS_New_API_Call_Per_User','When this alert fires, you should look at what APIs were called. We\'ve excluded some of the basic inaction ones (such as DescribeInstances), but the severity of the event will vary based on the severity of the API calls. The natural next step is to call the user and see if they expected this behavior. If the user cannot attribute this activity, it is best to reset the keys and continue your investigation to see what occurred.','2.0.0','The risk that this detection intends to reduce is the compromise of an AWS environment, where all of a sudden an account starts accessing AWS APIs that they haven\'t normally before (such as creating keys, creating AMIs, changing ACLs, etc.). Assuming that the user has not changed roles, and that new orchestration tools are not being used, this would suggest that credentials have been created or compromised, and are in control of an adversary. This could result in potential data leakage, data deletion, or cost run-up.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat'),(156,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Command and Control','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','DNS','This search is used to detect attempts to use DNS tunneling, by calculating the length of responses to DNS TXT queries. Endpoints using DNS as a method of transmission for data exfiltration, command and control, or evasion of security controls can often be detected by noting unusually large volumes of DNS traffic.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search uses the Network_Resolution data model and gathers all the answers to DNS queries for TXT records. The query then looks at the answer section and calculates the length of the answer. The search will then return information for those responses that exceed 100 characters in length.','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control',NULL,'Command and Control|Exfiltration','Detect Long DNS TXT Record Response','detection_long_dns_text_response',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Suspicious DNS Traffic','Advanced Threat Detection'),(157,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Detect evasion/escalation technique where the password of a privileged user reset by another authorized account this should be rare and supported by appropriate trouble ticketing and authentication of the requesting user.','Splunk Professional Services','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- PS Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','None',NULL,'None','Reset of password other than by self for privileged user','UC0106',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(158,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Web Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Web Server','Alerts when a host generates a lot of HTTP failures in a short span of time','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Excessive HTTP Failure Responses','excessive_http_failure_responses',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Application Security'),(159,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Account Compromise|IAM Analytics|Data Exfiltration|Network Attack|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_standard_deviation?ml_toolkit.dataset=AWS%20Unusual%20Amount%20of%20Modifications%20to%20ACLs%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail','Looks for a large number of Security Group ACL changes in a short period of time for a user.','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','AWS Unusual Amount of Modifications to ACLs - Demo\nAWS Unusual Amount of Modifications to ACLs - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Detect Spikes search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized AWS CloudTrail logs, during which someone does something bad. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the very standardized index and sourcetype for AWS CloudTrail, as detailed in How to Implement.','Yes','Assuming you use the ubiqutious AWS Add-on for Splunk to pull these logs in, this search should work automatically for you without issue. While implementing, make sure you follow the best pratice of specifying the index for your data.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,'<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately a spike in the number we\'re monitoring... it\'s nearly impossible for the math to lie. But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>How you handle these alerts depends on where you set the standard deviation. If you set a low standard deviation (2 or 3), you are likely to get a lot of events that are useful only for contextual information. If you set a high standard deviation (6 or 10), the amount of noise can be reduced enough to send an alert directly to analysts. If your orchestration tools will perform these actions, and they aren\'t a part of the baseline (or they\'re very rare in the baseline), those could create false positives. You might opt to whitelist those tools, or alternatively to make a part of the response verifying in your change management whether those tools were scheduled.</p>',NULL,'AWS Unusual Amount of Modifications to ACLs','AWS_Unusual_Amount_of_Modifications_to_ACLs','When this alert fires, you should call the user and see if they expected this behavior. If the user cannot attribute this activity, it is best to reset the keys and continue your investigation to see what occurred. In particular, look to see what the ACL changes were, to see what new access has been allowed. Check your VPC Flow logs to see if data was sent over those newly allowed connections.','2.0.0','The risk that this detection intends to reduce is the compromise of an AWS environment, where all of a sudden Security Group (Firewall) ACLs that have existed to protect an environment are thrown open, allowing either outside connections in, allowing data exfiltration, or allowing lateral movement from one group to another.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(160,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','High','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Command and Control','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','DNS','This search is used to detect DNS tunneling, by calculating the sum of the length of DNS queries and DNS answers. The search also filters out potential false positives by filtering out queries made to internal systems and the queries originating from internal DNS, Web, and Email servers. Endpoints using DNS as a method of transmission for data exfiltration, command and control, or evasion of security controls can often be detected by noting an unusually large volume of DNS traffic.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','The search will calculate the distinct count and sum of the length of DNS queries made and DNS answers received by a particular host to alert the analyst if the combined length is greater than 10000, which is not typical behavior.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control|Actions on Objective',NULL,'Command and Control|Exfiltration','Detection of DNS Tunnels','detection_dns_tunnelling',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Suspicious DNS Traffic','Advanced Threat Detection'),(161,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Accelerated','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Endpoint Compromise|Ransomware','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Detects an abnormally high number of endpoint changes by user account, as they relate to restarts, audits, filesystem, user, and registry modifications.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Abnormally High Number of Endpoint Changes By User','abnormally_high_number_of_endpoint_changes_by_user',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(162,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Detects gaps caused by the failure of the search head. If saved searches do not execute then there may be gaps in summary data.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Audit',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Potential Gap in Data','potential_gap_in_data',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(163,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=New%20Domain%20Name%20Detected%20-%20Demo','Authentication|Windows Security','<p>New AD domain names in your normal domain controller logs are a symptom of many Pass the Hash tools. While some of the latest don\'t produce these artifacts, this remains a very valuable detection mechanism.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','New Domain Name Detected - Demo\nNew Domain Name Detected - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our dataset is a anonymized collection of Windows logon events from a domain controller. For this analysis, we are looking for the earliest time for a domain name. We check if the first time that domain was seen was in the last day.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Installation','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>This search is designed to find older versions of Mimikatz (or other tools with similar techniques), and is not known to have any other false positives.</p>','Lateral Movement','New AD Domain Detected','showcase_new_ad_domain','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the account name associated with the new domain. Determine at what time the event occurred and from what system the login attempt occurred from. Contact the user and system owner(s) to determine if it is authorized, and document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted to determine is a pass the hash attack has been attempted and generated this new domain in the event log.</p>','1.0.0','<p>In Windows logs, the domain name is often reported when it\'s not explicitly required for the authentication. Under normal operation, the domain name reported will be totally normal, but when someone is intentionally modifiying authentication (such as with Pass the Hash), you can see incorrect, or empty domains. Pass the Hash is used by attackers to move laterally within the organization, connecting to new servers. While not all Pass the Hash techniques will demonstrate this vulnerability, tracking new domains in your Windows logs is very valuable.</p>',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Compliance'),(164,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Account Compromise|Data Exfiltration','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','VPN','Unusually Long VPN Session','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Unusually Long VPN Session','unusually_long_vpn_session',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring|Insider Threat'),(165,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Very High','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Operations|GDPR','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Succesful%20Backups%20-%20Demo','Backup','<p>With good backups, a ransomware attack goes from unrecoverable losses to a manageable nuisance. This shows how you can track successful backups.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Very High</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Operations','Demo Data\nLive Data','Succesful Backups - Demo\nSuccesful Backups - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','With sufficient backups that are maintained outside the local network, ransomware goes from unrecoverable losses to a manageable nuisance that consumes time. Organizations must track their back-up posture as a part of their overall corporate data availability and resiliency plan. This means knowing that routine backups are taking place and notifying the appropriate personnel when they are not. This use case helps Splunk users manage and verify that data resiliency processes are being conducted, specifically looking for indications of successful backups.','No','Because there are so many different strategies for backups and data resiliency, this search is provided as an example. In order to implement this, you need to obtain data from the backup logs on your endpoints, or from a central server responsible for performing the backups. In this case, we used netbackup as an example. Feel free to modify this search according to your backup solution and strategy.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,'None at the moment',NULL,'Monitor Successful Backups','sser_monitor_successful_backups','This search will let you know when one of your systems has been backed up. It will help you understand your environment and how often systems are backed up. You can use this knowledge in your risk assessment for your environment.','1.0.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(166,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for system processes that normally run out of C:\\Windows\\System32\\ that are not run from that location.  This can indicate a malicious process that is trying to hide as a legitimate process.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search returns all the processes that are not executing out of the C:\\Windows\\System32 directory. It then uses a regular expression to extract the file name of the running process. Next, it takes the filename and looks it up in a table of files that should normally run out of the C:\\Windows\\System32 directory. Any matches are then returned.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Defense Evasion','System Processes Run From Unexpected Locations','detection_system_processes_run_from_unexpected_locations',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Unusual Processes','Advanced Threat Detection'),(167,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Lateral Movement|Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Audit Trail','Alerts when numerous new accounts are created for a username accounts multiple hosts.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'New User Account Created On Multiple Hosts','new_user_account_created_on_multiple_hosts',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(168,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Very Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Data Exfiltration|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=AWS%20Public%20Bucket%20-%20Demo','Audit Trail','Detects when new or existing S3 buckets are set to public.','Splunk Security Essentials','Access','Demo Data\nLive Data','AWS Public Bucket - Demo\nAWS Public Bucket - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Simple Search Assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized AWS CloudTrail logs, where someone creates a public bucket. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the very standardized index and sourcetype for AWS CloudTrail, as detailed in How to Implement.','Yes','Assuming you use the ubiqutious AWS Add-on for Splunk to pull these logs in, this search should work automatically for you without issue. While implementing, make sure you follow the best pratice of specifying the index for your data.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3',NULL,'There are two types of undesired alerts that can occur from this search. One is when someone intentionally creates a public bucket -- you may wish to whitelist marketing employees that do this on a regular basis, or create a policy for how to create a public bucket, so that you can exclude it. The other is when someone creates a bucket that is public momentarily, but then they switch it back to private (discussed more in How To Respond).',NULL,'Public S3 Bucket in AWS','AWS_Public_Bucket','When this alert fires, there are three questions that should be asked -- is it still public, are the files public, and what is in it. The first is easy to detect -- just search your logs for the bucket name and PutBucketACL, you will see any subsequent ACL changes. The second and third are trickier, and require that server access logging is turned on for the S3 bucket (not done by default, and pretty inconvenient, so don\'t bet on it).','2.1.0','Open S3 Buckets are an extremely common way for breaches to occur these days. People host files for quick transfer but forget to take them down, or use S3 Buckets for backups of sensitive data but inadvertently mess up permissions. Newly created S3 buckets are monitored and data is quickly pulled. If you have a corporate AWS environment, you should prioritize analyzing any open S3 buckets. You may even wish to automate the remediation of them through AWS functions (<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/how-to-detect-and-automatically-remediate-unintended-permissions-in-amazon-s3-object-acls-with-cloudwatch-events/\">link</a>).',NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring|Advanced Threat Detection'),(169,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Hard','Medium','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Processes%20With%20High%20Entropy%20Names%20in%20Users%20Directory%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response|Windows Security','<p>Some malware will launch processes with randomized filenames.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Medium</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Processes With High Entropy Names in Users Directory - Demo\nProcesses With High Entropy Names in Users Directory - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Simple Search assistant. Our dataset is a collection of process launch logs (either Sysmon EventCode 1, or Windows Event ID 4688 -- either works). The search then leverages the URL Toolbox app from apps.splunk.com to determine entropy in the filename or file path. It takes filenames with the highest entropy, and surfaces them.</p>','No','Implementing this search is similar to any of the other searches that require EDR data. In order to use it, we need to get process launch events. For the demo and live version of this search we use Windows Security Event ID 4688, as it tends to be the most common, but you could apply it to any other data source that shows you launched processes -- just adjust the file path field (New_Process_Name) to match (it is not a CIM field).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Installation','<p>This search looks for potentially randomized filenames using Shannon Entropy. Entropy is a basic measure of randomness, but tends to become less accurate with longer strings. You should not review these alerts directly (except for access to extremely sensitive system), but instead use them for context, or to aggregate risk (as mentioned under How To Respond).</p>','Defense Evasion','Processes with High Entropy Names','showcase_high_entropy_processes','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and identify the file, path, user and system associated with this alert. Contact the user and system owner to determine if it is authorized, and document if it is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted as randomized file names on a system may serve as a way to mask malware.</p>','1.0.0','To avoid detection, malware often will launch malicious code with random filenames and/or paths. In this example, we use Shannon Entropy, provided by the URL Toolbox app, to identify these probable random names and report on them. Files with non-human-created character patterns are returned.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(170,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for registry activity associated with application compatibility shims, which can be leveraged by attackers for various nefarious purposes.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','In this search, we look for modifications to registry keys used for shim databases on Microsoft platforms via the object_category and object_path field in the Change_Analysis data model and give you the destination, command used to initiate the change, the user who conducted this activity, the resource affected(object), and the whole path of the object. An application compatibility shim is a small library that transparently intercepts an API (via hooking), changes the parameters passed, handles the operation itself, or redirects the operation elsewhere, such as additional code stored on a system. This capability can be also leveraged by attackers to create and store malicious files in a shim database as observed in CARBANAK backdoor.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Persistence','Registry Keys for Creating SHIM Databases','detection_malicious_application_shimming_via_registry',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Windows Persistence Techniques','Advanced Threat Detection'),(171,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Command and Control','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','DNS','This search allows you to identify the endpoints that have connected to more than five DNS servers over the timeframe of the search.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Communications with multiple DNS servers from a single client is unusual and may be indicative of malicious activity. This search works by performing a count by the source of the distinct destinations for the DNS traffic. The search uses the Network_Resolution data model.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Command and Control',NULL,'Command and Control|Exfiltration','Clients Connecting to Multiple DNS Servers','detection_clients_connecting_to_multiple_dns_servers',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Suspicious DNS Traffic','Advanced Threat Detection'),(172,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Scanning','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Web Server','This search looks for specific GET/HEAD requests to web servers that are indicative of reconnaissance attempts to identify vulnerable JBOSS servers. JexBoss is described as the exploit tool of choice for this malicious activity.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search returns the number of times a URL associated with this type of JexBoss probe is observed.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','Reconnaissance',NULL,'Discovery','Detect attackers scanning for vulnerable JBOSS servers','detection_attackers_scanning_for_vulnerable_jboss_servers',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'JBOSS Vulnerability','Security Monitoring'),(173,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_first_seen_demo?ml_toolkit.dataset=Suspicious%20Command%20Launch%20-%20Demo','Endpoint Detection and Response|Windows Security','<p>Some files rarely get used by legitimate activities, such as at.exe. This search will detect those executables being launched, regardless of the circumstance. (<a href=\"https://car.mitre.org/wiki/CAR-2013-05-004\">MITRE CAR Reference</a>)</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Suspicious Command Launch - Demo\nSuspicious Command Launch - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect New Values search assistant. Our dataset is a anonymized collection of process launch events (Event ID 4688) filtered for suspicious filenames (from a lookup called tools.csv). We check the first time that\'s occurred per path, per user, and then alert if that was in the last day.</p>','No','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the First Time Seen examples) is generally very simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted.</li><li>Save the search.</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend leveraging a lookup cache. For more on this, see the lookup cache dropdown below and select the sample item. A window will pop up telling you more about this feature.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Exploitation','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately reflect the first occurrence in the time period you\'re searching over (or for the lookup cache feature, the first occurrence over whatever time period you built the lookup). But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>There are no known false positives for this search apart from some custom-designed scripts and the occasional sysadmin familiar with it. Both of these should be very easy to filter out.</p>','Discovery|Lateral Movement|Execution','New Suspicious Executable Launch for User','showcase_new_suspicious_exe_launch_for_user','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and capture the time of the event, executable, its associated path, the system, user and other pertinent information. Contact the owner of the systems. If it is authorized, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials have been used by another party and additional investigation.</p>','1.0.0','There are certain executables launched on endpoints that generally mean that someone, or something, is up to no good. For this example, we have provided a lookup file ??tools.csv?? that among other things identifies binaries by executable name as being used for discovery or attack purposes. It may be perfectly normal for one or more of these executables to launch on a given endpoint, but if one of these executables is seen where it hasn??t been seen before, this can be considered an alert-able condition.',NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection'),(174,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Ransomware','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','The vssadmin.exe utiltiy is used to interact with the Volume Shadow Copy Service.  Wmic is an interface to the Windows Management Instrumentation.  This search looks for either of these tools being used to delete shadow copies.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks for execution of vssadmin or wmic with both the \"delete\" and \"shadows\" parameters passed on the command line. The two arguments are searched for separately because we can\'t predict the number of spaces between the words on the command line. The search will return the number of times this activity was observed, and the times of the first and last event.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Execution','Deleting Shadow Copies','detection_delete_shadow_copies',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Windows Log Manipulation','Security Monitoring'),(175,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Medium','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','Detects cleartext passwords being stored at rest (such as in the Unix passwd file)','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Cleartext Password At Rest Detected','cleartext_password_at_rest_detected',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Compliance'),(176,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Endpoint Compromise|Threat Intelligence|Unauthorized Software|Operations','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Network Communication','Blacklisted Application','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Blacklisted Application','blacklisted_application',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Advanced Threat Detection|Security Monitoring|Security Monitoring'),(177,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Insider Threat','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','Network Communication','Flight Risk User','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Flight Risk User','flight_risk_user',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Insider Threat'),(178,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Web Attack','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Web Server','This search looks for long URLs that have several SQL commands visible within them.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Network',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','This search looks only at your web servers and returns the source, the web server, the URL and its length, and the user agent associated with HTTP GET requests for extremely long URLs or user agent lengths with more than three common SQL commands found within the URL.','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_2','Delivery',NULL,'Defense Evasion|Execution','SQL Injection with Long URLs','detection_sql_injection_with_long_urls',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'SQL Injection','Application Security'),(179,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Hard','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Data Exfiltration|Endpoint Compromise|SaaS','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_standard_deviation?ml_toolkit.dataset=Spike%20in%20Email%20from%20Address%20-%20Demo','Email','<p>Both to detect data exfiltration and compromised account, we can analyze users that are sending out dramatically more data than normal. This search looks per source email address for big increases in volume.</p><p><b>Alert Volume:</b> Low</p>','Splunk Security Essentials','Network','Demo Data\nLive Data','Spike in Email from Address - Demo\nSpike in Email from Address - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','<p>This example leverages the Detect Spikes (standard deviation) search assistant. Our dataset is an anonymized collection of email logs centered around a particular user for a month.</p>','Yes','<p>Implementation of this example (or any of the Time Series Spike / Standard Deviation examples) is generally pretty simple. <ul><li>Validate that you have the right data onboarded, and that the fields you want to monitor are properly extracted. If the base search you see in the box below returns results.</li><li>Save the search to run over a long period of time (recommended: at least 30 days).</li></ul></p><p>For most environments, these searches can be run once a day, often overnight, without worrying too much about a slow search. If you wish to run this search more frequently, or if this search is too slow for your envionment, we recommend using a summary index that first aggregates the data. We will have documentation for this process shortly, but for now you can look at Summary Indexing descriptions such as <a href=\"http://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/SplunkCloud/6.6.3/Knowledge/Usesummaryindexing\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://www.davidveuve.com/tech/how-i-do-summary-indexing-in-splunk/\">here</a>.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective','<p class=\"disclaimer\">This is a strictly behavioral search, so we define \"false positive\" slightly differently. Every time this fires, it will accurately a spike in the number we\'re monitoring... it\'s nearly impossible for the math to lie. But while there are really no \"false positives\" in a traditional sense, there is definitely lots of noise.</p> <p>How you handle these alerts depends on where you set the standard deviation. If you set a low standard deviation (2 or 3), you are likely to get a lot of events that are useful only for contextual information. If you set a high standard deviation (6 or 10), the amount of noise can be reduced enough to send an alert directly to analysts.</p>','Exfiltration','User with Increase in Outgoing Email','showcase_spike_in_outgoing_email','<p>When this search returns values, initiate your incident response process and capture the time of the event, the sender, recipient, subject or the mail and attachments, if any. Contact the sender. If it is authorized behavior, document that this is authorized and by whom. If not, the user credentials may have been used by another party and additional investigation is warranted.</p>','1.2.0',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat'),(180,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','High','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Authentication','This search looks for specific authentication events from the Windows Security Event logs to detect potential attempts at using the Pass-the-Hash technique.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Access',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','To detect pass the hash activity, we look at all events with event code 4624 or 4625 that specify a logon type 3 (network logons). We are looking for the NtLmSsP account, with a key length set to 0. These indicate lower level protocols that are typically used through Pass the Hash (WMI, SMB, etc.). The search also filters out events with an account name of \'Anonymous\' to help reduce false positives.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Lateral Movement','Detect Activity Related to Pass the Hash Attacks','detection_activity_related_to_pass_the_hash',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Lateral Movement','Advanced Threat Detection'),(181,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Advanced','Other','Splunk_App_for_Enterprise_Security','Other','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ES_Use_Case','Any Host Logs','Alerts when an event is discovered including text has been identified as important. This rule triggers whenever an event is discovered with the tag of &quot;watchlist&quot;.','Splunk App for Enterprise Security','Threat',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- ES Use Case','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Watchlisted Event Observed','watchlisted_event_observed',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Other'),(182,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Medium','Enterprise_Security_Content_Update','Lateral Movement','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/ESCU_Use_Case','Endpoint Detection and Response','This search looks for flags passed to schtasks.exe on the command line that indicate a job is being scheduled on a remote system.','Enterprise Security Content Update','Endpoint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','The search looks for execution of schtasks.exe with parameters that indicate a task is being scheduled on a remote host. Schtasks.exe is a native windows program that is used to schedule tasks on local or remote systems. Attackers often leverage this capability to schedule the execution of commands or malicious executables on remote systems.','No',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_3','Actions on Objective',NULL,'Persistence|Lateral Movement|Execution','Schtasks scheduling job on remote system','detection_schtasks_scheduling_job_on_remote_system',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Lateral Movement','Advanced Threat Detection'),(183,NULL,'dinglingfeng',NULL,'Other','Splunk_User_Behavior_Analytics','Lateral Movement|Insider Threat|Account Compromise|IAM Analytics','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/UBA_Use_Case','VPN','Unusual AD Event','Splunk User Behavior Analytics','Other',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No','Help not needed -- UBA Use Case','Yes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_4','None',NULL,'None','Unusual AD Event','unusual_ad_event',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Advanced Threat Detection|Insider Threat|Security Monitoring|Compliance'),(184,NULL,'dinglingfeng','Basic','Low','Splunk_Security_Essentials','Endpoint Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/showcase_simple_search?ml_toolkit.dataset=Multiple%20Infections%20on%20Host%20-%20Demo','Anti-Virus','Finds hosts that have logged multiple different infections in a short period of time.','Splunk Security Essentials','Endpoint','Demo Data\nLive Data','Multiple Infections on Host - Demo\nMultiple Infections on Host - Live',NULL,NULL,'Yes','This example leverages the Simple Search search assistant. Our example dataset is a collection of anonymized Symantec Endpoint Protection logs (onboarded in accordance with our Data Onboarding Guides), during which someone does something bad. Our live search looks for the same behavior using the standardized sourcetypes for Symantec Endpoint Protection or the Common Information Model.','Yes','With Symantec logs onboard, these searches should work easily. If you have a different Anti-Virus product, they should be very easy to adapt to the field names and sourcetypes for that product -- particularly if you use a Splunk Add-on that maps them to the Common Information Model (search on Splunkbase!).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stage_1',NULL,'No known false positives.',NULL,'Multiple Infections on Host','Multiple_Infections_on_Host','When multiple infections occur to the same host, your response plan should be the same as any malware event, just with greater urgency.','2.0.0','Viruses happen, but multiple viruses at once are a greater concern, as it could indicate an exploit kit that tries several techniques where some might succeed, or just a host with multiple unrelated viruses. Those hosts should be prioritized and investigated immediately to see what else might not have been caught.',NULL,NULL,'Security Monitoring'),(185,NULL,'dinglingfeng','None','Other','Splunk_Professional_Services','Account Compromise','http://10.145.89.71:8000/en-US/app/Splunk_Security_Essentials/PS_Use_Case','Authentication','For employers that allow remote external connectivity the detection of two or more distinct values of external source IP address for successful authentications to a